{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":17803,"record_hash":"sha256:f98126ba78afaf8a1b01465c7afc741be5781728ac2ff3fd85cd8862761b1255","timestamp":"2026-05-10T07:16:56.389Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I cloned it to [/Users/kiril/src/cli](/Users/kiril/src/cli). Short version: [entireio/cli](https://github.com/entireio/cli) is useful as a reference, but I would not import its transcript model wholesale.\n\nThe highest-signal bits:\n\n1. **They preserve native transcripts, then build compact views**\n   Their architecture docs explicitly avoid inventing one universal transcript format and emphasize keeping the full native transcript for portability/resume. See [/Users/kiril/src/cli/docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md](/Users/kiril/src/cli/docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md:1).  \n   This mostly validates our `source_record` approach, with one caveat: our redacted GitMeta data is good for browsing/context/handoff, but exact same-agent resume may eventually need either native transcript preservation or provider-specific reconstruction.\n\n2. **Claude and Cursor can share a loose JSONL shape**\n   Their shared transcript parser treats Claude’s `type` and Cursor’s `role` as equivalent-ish fields: [/Users/kiril/src/cli/cmd/entire/cli/transcript/types.go](/Users/kiril/src/cli/cmd/entire/cli/transcript/types.go:19), [/Users/kiril/src/cli/cmd/entire/cli/transcript/parse.go](/Users/kiril/src/cli/cmd/entire/cli/transcript/parse.go:100).  \n   This supports our instinct to keep provider parsing narrow but normalize into one small transcript record shape.\n\n3. **Codex parsing has useful future lessons**\n   Their Codex parser handles `session_meta`, `turn_context`, `response_item`, and `event_msg`, and groups tool calls/results for compact display: [/Users/kiril/src/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/codex/transcript.go](/Users/kiril/src/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/codex/transcript.go:1), [/Users/kiril/src/cli/cmd/entire/cli/transcript/compact/codex.go](/Users/kiril/src/cli/cmd/entire/cli/transcript/compact/codex.go:72).  \n   I would not add grouping now, but future web views will probably want a provider-specific rendering/compaction pass over our stored chronological records.\n\n4. **Role enum still seems fine**\n   They mostly model `user` and `assistant`, but their Codex fixtures include `developer` as internal/system-injected content. Claude also has odd records like `progress`, `system`, and snapshots.  \n   Our minimal role enum still feels reasonable. One tiny future tweak may be mapping Claude/Cursor `\"human\"` to `Role::User`, since Entire does that in compact parsing.\n\n5. **Cursor is indeed different enough to defer**\n   Cursor stores transcripts under `~/.cursor/projects/<sanitized-repo>/agent-transcripts`, with both flat and nested layouts: [/Users/kiril/src/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/cursor/cursor.go](/Users/kiril/src/cli/cmd/entire/cli/agent/cursor/cursor.go:72). It also sometimes has `transcript_path: null` and resolves from conversation id.  \n   That matches our earlier caution: useful to document later discovery, but not worth pulling into the POC yet.\n\n6. **Their redaction choices support our current direction**\n   Entire uses Betterleaks plus entropy and credential patterns: [/Users/kiril/src/cli/redact/redact.go](/Users/kiril/src/cli/redact/redact.go:1). Notably, their high-entropy token regex avoids `/`, which lines up with the path/base64 tension we kept tightening in our redactor.\n\nMy take: the main thing worth borrowing now is not code, but a design note: **store chronological redacted source records now; leave provider-specific compaction/rendering/resume reconstruction as later layers.** That keeps the POC small while preserving the path toward both future use cases.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-10T07:16:56.389Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}